@anchor{boxplot}
@anchor{boxplot_description}
@deffn  {Function} boxplot (@var{data})
@deffnx {Function} boxplot (@var{data}, @var{option_1}, @var{option_2}, @dots{})
@deffnx {Function} boxplot_description (@dots{})

This function plots box-and-whishker diagrams.  Argument @var{data} can be a
list, which is not of great interest, since these diagrams are mainly used for
comparing different samples, or a matrix, so it is possible to compare
two or more components of a multivariate statistical variable.
But it is also allowed @var{data} to be a list of samples with 
possible different sample sizes, in fact this is the only function 
in package @code{descriptive} that admits this type of data structure.

Available options are:

@itemize @bullet

@item
@var{box_width} (default, @code{3/4}): relative width of boxes.
This value must be in the range @code{[0,1]}.

@item
@var{box_orientation} (default, @code{vertical}): possible values:
@code{vertical} and @code{horizontal}.

@item
All @code{draw} options, except @code{points_joined}, @code{point_size},
@code{point_type}, @code{xtics}, @code{ytics}, @code{xrange}, and @code{yrange},
which are internally assigned by @code{boxplot}.
If you want to set your own values for this options or want to build
complex scenes, make use of @code{boxplot_description}.

@item
The following local @code{draw} options: @code{key}, @code{color}, 
and @code{line_width}.

@end itemize

Function @code{boxplot_description} creates a graphic object
suitable for creating complex scenes, together with other
graphic objects.  There is also a function @code{wxboxplot} for 
creating embedded histograms in interfaces wxMaxima and iMaxima.

Examples:

Box-and-whishker diagram from a multivariate sample.

@example
(%i1) load (descriptive)$
(%i2) s2 : read_matrix(file_search("wind.data"))$
@group
(%i3) boxplot(s2,
        box_width  = 0.2,
        title      = "Windspeed in knots",
        xlabel     = "Stations",
        color      = red,
        line_width = 2)$
@end group
@end example

Box-and-whishker diagram from three samples of different sizes.

@example
(%i1) load (descriptive)$
@group
(%i2) A :
       [[6, 4, 6, 2, 4, 8, 6, 4, 6, 4, 3, 2],
        [8, 10, 7, 9, 12, 8, 10],
        [16, 13, 17, 12, 11, 18, 13, 18, 14, 12]]$
@end group
(%i3) boxplot (A, box_orientation = horizontal)$
@end example
@end deffn

